Credit Card Fraud Detection

An end-to-end machine learning pipeline that detects fraudulent credit card transactions from a highly imbalanced dataset of 284,807 real-world transactions. The project addresses the core challenge of fraud detection — extreme class imbalance (only 0.17% fraud) — using SMOTE oversampling and evaluates models using business-relevant metrics beyond simple accuracy.
⸻
Problem Statement

In fraud detection, accuracy alone is misleading. A naive model that labels every transaction as legitimate achieves 99.83% accuracy — yet catches zero fraud. This project builds a robust classification pipeline that maximises precision and recall on the fraud class, minimising both false negatives (missed fraud) and false positives (wrongly flagged customers).
⸻
 Dataset

- Source: Credit Card Fraud Detection — Kaggle (ULB)
- Size: 284,807 transactions × 31 features
- Fraud rate: 0.17% (492 fraud cases out of 284,807)
- Features: V1–V28 (PCA-anonymised), Time, Amount, Class
- Target: Class — 0 = Legitimate, 1 = Fraud

Download creditcard.csv from the Kaggle link above and place it in the project root before running.
