Methodology

1. Exploratory Data Analysis
- Class distribution analysis — confirmed extreme imbalance (0.17% fraud)
- Transaction amount and time distribution by class
- Correlation heatmap across PCA features (V1–V28), Amount, and Class
- Key finding: V14, V17, V12, V10 show strongest negative correlation with fraud class

2. Feature Engineering
- Standardised Amount and Time using StandardScaler (V1–V28 already PCA-transformed)
- Dropped raw Amount and Time columns after scaling

3. Handling Class Imbalance — SMOTE
- Applied SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) exclusively on training data to prevent data leakage
- Balanced training set from 0.17% fraud → 50/50 split
- Compared against random under-sampling — SMOTE preserved more information from legitimate transactions

4. Model Training & Comparison
Model	Accuracy	Precision	Recall	F1-Score	ROC-AUC
Logistic Regression (baseline)	97.4%	0.94	0.81	0.87	0.97
Random Forest (selected)	99.6%	0.987	0.878	0.881	0.989

Random Forest selected — superior precision and AUC, minimising false positives on legitimate transactions while maintaining high fraud recall.

5. Evaluation Strategy
- Confusion matrix — visualise actual false positives and false negatives
- Precision — of all flagged fraud, how many were real? (minimise customer disruption)
- Recall — of all actual fraud, how many were caught? (minimise financial loss)
- F1-Score — harmonic mean balancing precision and recall
- ROC-AUC — model discrimination across all classification thresholds

6. Prediction System
- Trained model serialised with pickle
- End-to-end inference on new transactions: input raw features → outputs FRAUD / LEGITIMATE with probability score
⸻
Key Findings

- Accuracy is insufficient for imbalanced fraud datasets — precision, recall, and AUC are the correct metrics
- V14, V17, V12 are the most important features for fraud classification — their PCA components likely encode transaction velocity and amount deviation patterns
- SMOTE outperformed under-sampling — preserving all 284K legitimate transactions in training improved generalisation
- Random Forest's ensemble approach handles the non-linear decision boundary between fraud and legitimate transactions significantly better than logistic regression
